article.description:
Katie Douglas matched a career high
with 28 points, including 20 in the second half, and Erin Phillips
added a career-high 19 points as the Connecticut Sun beat the
Washington Mystics 86-73 on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Douglas drops 20 in second half as Sun win
article.linkText: Douglas drops 20 in second half as Sun win
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Connecticut coach Mike Thibault tried
to revitalize his team at halftime after the Sun lost a 12-point
lead and fell behind by four at the break to the Washington
Mystics.

"I asked my players at halftime, 'Who kidnapped my team in the
second quarter?' I didn't recognize the team that was out there in
the second quarter," Thibault said. "We didn't play anything like
we did in the first quarter. We lost our pace of the game. We lost
our defensive focus for a bit."

The Sun responded to the speech with a 16-4 run to open the
third quarter on the way to an 86-73 win over the Mystics on
Tuesday night.

Katie Douglas matched a career high with 28 points, including 20
in the second half, to lead five Sun players in double figures.
Erin Phillips added a career-high 19 points.

"There's definitely times when I can step up, but that's what
makes our team so dangerous," Douglas said. "At any times, any
one of us can step up. ... We're all capable, which creates
defensive nightmares."

Phillips scored 11 in the first half to help the Eastern
Conference-leading Sun jump out to a 12-point first-quarter lead.
She finished 6-for-9 from the floor and 4-for-7 from 3-point range.

"And then she energized us when we went flat a little bit by
chasing down long rebounds and loose balls," Thibault said.

Taj McWilliams-Franklin and Margo Dydek each scored 11 points
for the Sun. McWilliams-Franklin also had 12 rebounds to match her
own franchise record of eight double-doubles in a season. She also
had six assists. Dydek added seven rebounds and four blocks.
Lindsay Whalen finished with 10 points.

DeLisha Milton-Jones scored 17 points and pulled down seven
rebounds to pace the Mystics. Tamara James (13 points) and Coco
Miller (10 points) led the Mystics' reserves, who outscored the
Sun's bench 36-7.

Washington leading-scorer Alana Beard spent much of the second
half in foul trouble and was held to nine points.

"Alana had 30 points (Sunday against the Seattle Storm) and she
was phenomenal," Washington coach Richie Adubato said. "The same
shots that she made the other night she missed tonight. Our
starting group was 15-for-49. Against a team as good as
Connecticut, you have to shoot the ball. Our first team did not
shoot it well at all tonight."

The Sun's lack of energy allowed the Mystics, who hold fourth
place in the Eastern Conference, to open the second quarter with a
12-1 run, fueling a rally that led to a 40-36 Washington lead at
halftime.

The Sun came back to outscore the Mystics 30-15 in the third to
take control of the game.

Washington scored the first six points of the fourth quarter to
cut its deficit to 66-61 with 7:31 to play, but a pair of free
throws by Whalen and five straight points by Douglas started a 12-2
Sun run that put the game out of reach.
